<TEXT>
utah is a state of large closeknit 
families whose religion frowns on the use of liquor and caffeine 
it is also a state with the nations largest appetite for the 
stimulant drug ritalin 
the drug enforcement administration said that in 1986 pharmacies 
along the states wasatch front received 25000 grams of the drug 
used for hyperactive children or 1558 grams for every 100000 
population 
that figure compares to 1218 grams per 100000 residents of 
maryland the next highest ritalin state in new york the figure 
was 347 grams per 100000 
the reasons for utahs high use of ritalin are many they may 
point the way for the future in other parts of the country 
what we are doing here is in some ways ahead of many parts 
of the country said paul wender a psychiatrist and researcher 
at the university of utah 
utah has the youngest population of any state with nearly a 
quarter of its residents aged 5 to 17 it also leads the nation in 
the size of individual families about 43 children per household 
consequently it has the nations most crowded classrooms with 
246 students per teacher although utah ranks near the top of the 
list in the amount of state money 47 percent going to education 
it is last in per capita spending on education at 2372 per 
student 
so when the fragile balance in these overcrowded classrooms is 
threatened by disruptive children the pressures on parents and 
teachers are going to lead people to look for solutions and one 
of the solutions is medication said stevan kukic state director 
of special education 
in the salt lake school district an estimated 2 percent of the 
60000 students receive ritalin or one of its cousins for attention 
deficit disorder a syndrome that includes hyperactive as well as 
inattentive pupils 
it is becoming more acceptable in the parents minds and the 
teachers minds said julie miller a special education teacher 
whose son takes ritalin when the teachers see the dramatic 
effect it can have on problem students they want them medicated so 
they can learn 
sam goldstein a psychologist who saw 100 add children at his 
clinic last year estimates a quarter of his patients are referred 
by the schools another 25 percent come at the suggestion of other 
parents whose children take ritalin half his patients were sent by 
pediatricans 
utahs medical community also contributes to ritalin use 
reseachers at the university of utah are considered leaders in add 
study their philosophies are passed on to their students many of 
whom later set up practice nearby 
as a result salt lake has three clinics that specialize in the 
diagnosis and treatment of add children many larger cities across 
the country have none psychologists psychiatrists and 
pediatricians share information and refer patients for treatment 
in a community this size it is easier to make an impact with 
an idea especially an idea that appeals to people said 
goldstein 
parents of add children describe their successes with ritalin as 
more than appealing kathy miner cries when she talks about the 
effect ritalin has had on her 11yearold son jeremy 
there has been such a remarkable change in this child she 
said from the time he was 7 he talked about suicide now hes on 
the student council and is so thrilled with life 
mrs miner has joined others in a local support group for add 
parents the gatherings can be emotional laughter about the 
bruises and stitches their children have collected while rocketing 
around the house tears as they talk about the difference treatment 
has brought 
i wanted to share the knowledge with other families said 
the groups founder terri steineckert whose son tyler 11 has 
taken ritalin for more than a year it is very traumatic to put a 
child on drugs but if you have a good experience youre 
converted she said 
</TEXT>
