in turning to john shepherd a former american 
bar association president to fill the no 2 position at the 
justice department attorney general edwin meese iii has found a 
strong conservative ally 
shepherd a 62yearold st louis attorney wrote a 3400word 
article last september for the national law journal supporting 
president reagans nomination of judge robert bork to the supreme 
court and attacking borks critics 
on the eve of hearings into the nomination later rejected by 
the senate shepherd said borks philosophy that courts should 
restrain themselves in interpreting the constitution is 
synonymous with judicial integrity 
far from being an unprincipled activist judge bork is a 
highly principled jurist well within the jurisprudential 
mainstream shepherd wrote 
but prior to serving as the president of the 340000member aba 
in 1984 and 1985 shepherd was well known to conservative activists 
in key policy roles in the reagan administration 
in 1977 he first came to the attention of california 
conservatives then behind the effort to get ronald reagan elected 
president in 1980 
while representing the hoover institute associated with stanford 
university in a case then shepherd met most of the officers of the 
conservative think tank that provided much of the philosophic 
underpinning for the socalled reagan revolution within a year 
shepherd was named an overseer of the institute 
shepherd started his practice after getting a law degree from 
st louis university in 1951 representing personal injury victims 
in liability suits often on a contingency fee basis getting paid a 
percentage of any settlement or damages awarded 
as the bar associations president he vigorously defended that 
practice against assaults by the medical community in response to 
mounting malpractice claims and other defendants in liability suits 
contingency fees are a nocure nopay system that is the key 
to the courthouse for many many citizens he said jurors have 
to understand that marcus welby is not our system of medical care 
however shepherd also recognized that lawyers also have an 
image problem he released during his tenure as the abas president 
a fiveyear study concluding that attorneys could reduce their 
clients legal costs by 75 percent through better management 
we must move in that direction he said 
during that time his law practice also prospered setting up his 
own firm shepherd sandberg amp phoenix in st louis in 1980 
shepherd evolved from a plaintiffs attorney to a defense lawyer in 
liability cases 
his firms clients now include some of the nations corporate 
giants among them the monsanto co general dynamics and ford 
motor co 
a former bookkeeper from shepherds law firm who claimed she had 
an affair with shepherd went on trial in st louis circuit court 
last month and was convicted of stealing more than 147000 from 
the firm 
denise sinner who was fired in february 1987 was accused of 
writing checks to herself from the law firms accounts and admitted 
using the money to pay bills and buy luxury items 
she claimed shepherd had told her to write checks to herself 
but shepherd denied that he had had an affair with her or that he 
had authorized her to write the checks 
sinner 29 also was convicted of making a false statement to 
the government she had claimed that a doctor had diagnosed her as 
having terminal cancer 
