<TEXT>
milwaukee voters tuesday elected a mayor who promised real 
change after retiring mayor henry maiers nearly three decades in 
office and voters in tulsa okla unseated their republican mayor 
jesse jacksons clout was demonstrated in defeat of a charter 
amendment in cleveland while in columbia mo mayor rodney smith 
survived a recall election that resulted from a controversy with 
racial overtones 
wisconsin state sen john norquist swept to victory over former 
acting gov martin schreiber in the nonpartisan race to succeed 
maier who is retiring at age 70 after holding the office since 
1960 
together we built a grassroots volunteer organization like 
milwaukee has never seen norquist told cheering backers at his 
victory party together we delivered a message of hope and a 
message of real change and together we will make this message a 
reality in milwaukee 
complete unofficial returns from all 324 precincts showed the 
38yearold norquist with 112902 votes or 54 percent and 
schreiber with 93738 votes or 45 percent 
roughly 26 percent of clevelands registered voters turned out 
for the charter referendum unofficial returns showed 46854 votes 
against the measure or 65 percent to 25458 in favor or 35 
percent 
jackson the democratic presidential contender lent his support 
to opponents of the amendment to limit the city council president 
to two oneyear terms 
the ballot issue was viewed by many as an attack on city council 
president george forbes who has led the council for 15 years and 
is the citys highest black elected official 
the coalition for ordinance reforming councils efficiency 
known as cforce led a petition drive to get the amendment on the 
ballot cforce leaders including blacks contend forbes has 
intimidated council members by withholding federal money for ward 
projects and stalling legislation 
jacksons picture was used on literature against the amendment 
and a radio advertisement featured jackson urging voters to defeat 
the charter amendment 
jackson recorded an audio tape in which he claims that tuesdays 
special election on the amendment is an attempt to take away what 
we have gained across the years a share of power in cleveland and 
across the nation said gerald j austin jacksons national 
campaign manager 
columbia mayor smith a 59yearold selfemployed tree surgeon 
elected as a writein candidate in 1986 faced a recall election 
because of controversy over remarks he made last october at a 
meeting with local blacks angry over the forced resignation of 
police chief bill dye a black 
the mayor who is white told a predominantly black crowd that 
if they didnt like columbia they ought to leave 
in the annals of black history we are always told to move and 
give up our rights said betty roberts a leader of the coalition 
of concerned citizens which organized the recall drive 
final returns showed 2493 voters or 22 percent favored 
recalling the selfemployed tree surgeon while 9041 voters or 78 
percent wanted him to remain in office 
five candidates were running for mayor in tulsa where a number 
of other local offices were being decided 
final unofficial returns showed state sen rodger randle a 
democrat had 45517 votes or 553 percent to republican 
incumbent dick crawfords 28142 votes or 342 percent 
in kenosha wis a city rocked by chrysler corps announced 
closing of an auto plant incumbent mayor eugene dorff lost a bid 
to win his first full term with 33 of 34 precincts reporting 
unofficial returns showed alderman pat moran with 12329 votes to 
10130 for dorff 
in milwaukee support in the black community became a heated 
campaign issue when black businessman lee holloway who finished 
third in the feb 16 primary held a rally to endorse a candidate 
while paying off remaining campaign debts norquist boycotted the 
event and its 20 admission fee schreiber attended and won the 
endorsement 
norquist was elected to the state assembly in 1974 and served 
there until being elected in 1982 to the senate where he was 
assistant majority leader 
schreiber a lawyer served in the state senate from 1962 until 
being elected lieutenant governor in 1970 then was acting governor 
after gov patrick j lucey resigned to become us ambassador to 
mexico in 1977 
schreiber lost to republican lee s dreyfus in the 1978 election 
for governor he lost again when he tried for the democratic 
nomination for governor in 1982 and has worked at jobs in the 
private sector 
