<TEXT>
benjamin and patrick binder who spent their 
first seven months joined at the head are seriously underdeveloped 
but have the potential to lead normal lives said doctors preparing 
to release the babies from the hospital 
the separated siamese twins now 14 months old will return to 
germany in the next few days physicians at johns hopkins hospital 
said tuesday benjamin should begin crawling soon and will go home 
to ulm west germany with his parents patrick will go to a german 
hospital for observation 
there is no reason for us to think they will not continue to 
improve said dr ben carson a member of the medical team that 
has treated the infants since they were admitted in august 
they have made very substantial progress in the past few 
months and were very hopeful the potential will culminate in 
normal existence carson said at a news conference 
however dr mark rogers stressed that the boys are not now 
normal their development is equivalent to that of 2to5monthold 
babies 
carson said he was unwilling to project the mental and physical 
level the boys will reach but when the twins return here for 
evaluation next year doctors will be able to predict fairly 
accurately the boys future development 
the twins have had several setbacks since they were separated in 
a 22hour operation during the labor day weekend by a 70member 
medical team in october their temperatures rose inexplicably for 
several days the latest occurred march 13 when patrick choked on 
formula fed to him through a nasal tube 
rogers said its unknown if the incident will have longterm 
effects although patrick had reached the point of turning over 
before the incident and has not returned to that level 
benjamin is at about the level as when he entered the hospital 
and is expected to begin crawling soon the doctors said 
because they were joined at the head the twins were not 
normally developed when they arrived the trauma of the operation 
and long hospital stay account at least partially for the 
developmental lag carson said 
at the time of the separation operation doctors had given it a 
5050 chance of success 
certainly in terms of a medical or technical feat it has 
clearly been successful carson said 
he said there were 48 cases in medical history of siamese twins 
joined at the head this was the first separation where both twins 
lived their kind of joining at the back of the head with a 
shared vein was the rarest he said 
in february doctors implanted titanium mesh plates in the 
opening at the back of their heads created by the separation of 
their joined skulls and a shared vein 
benjamin has a bald spot on the back of his head from the 
operation but if he grows his hair long he can comb it down 
said dr craig dufresne patrick has a full head of hair 
the twins parents have refused to speak with reporters here 
before the separation at hopkins they sold their story to a west 
german magazine 
