<TEXT>
hungary on wednesday launched its 
strongest criticism yet on communist ally romania over an ethnic 
dispute that has clouded relations between the warsaw pact 
neighbors for two years 
two hungarian newspapers printed editorials fiercely critical of 
a reported romanian move to use only romanianlanguage place names 
for cities and villages traditionally known to romanias german and 
hungarian ethnic minorities in their own languages 
about 17 million hungarians and 220000 ethnic germans live in 
romania mostly in the central province of transylvania hungary 
has expressed mounting concern over what it says are romanian moves 
to cut back hungarianlanguage education and disperse the minority 
throughout romania 
romania charges that hungarys complaints mask an effort by 
budapest to regain transylvania which was ruled by hungary for 
several centuries but given to romania after world war i 
both claim that transylvania is the area where their nations 
were first settled and they have squabbled over the region for 
decades 
in the past two years however the dispute has escalated 
pointing up the difference between hungarys reformist communism 
and the tight rule of president nicolae ceausescu in romania which 
is increasingly isolated from its east bloc allies 
the government daily magyar hirlap said violations of minority 
rights to maintain their own language and culture can neither be 
understood or accepted at the end of the 20th century on our 
continent 
the harsh editorial stopped short of blaming ceausescu for the 
move to use only romanian place names but said it could hardly 
be a local excess since to our knowledge the strings reach 
much higher 
another daily magyar nemzet condemned ceausescus recently 
announced program to wipe out up to 7000 villages in romania by 
the year 2000 as drastic demolition and an attempt to quash 
romanian hungarian and other minority cultures 
magyar hirlap also took romania to task for its unprecedented 
action in denying hungarys bucharest ambassador a traditional 
address on national radio and television to mark hungarys 
liberation day april 4 
the newspaper noted this was a break with tradition and said 
without further detail that it is regrettable that such themes 
can emerge between two neighboring socialist countries 
western analysts said wednesdays attacks were the sharpest yet 
in the war of words between the nations 
hungarian dissidents who demonstrated for human rights in 
romania outside the romanian embassy in budapest on feb 1 have 
charged the budapest government is to some extent exploiting 
popular hungarian unease about the treatment of ethnic hungarians 
in romania to divert attention from the countrys economic crisis 
but hungary took unprecedented action last month when it 
approved spending about 6 million to help an estimated 10000 
refugees who have fled the shortages and harsh living conditions in 
romania for hungary many but not all of the refugees are ethnic 
hungarians 
