vanessa redgrave deserves damages from the boston 
symphony orchestra because its cancellation of her performances 
after receiving protest threats violated her civil rights her 
attorney told a federal appeals court wednesday 
a symphony attorney however countered that massachusetts law 
allowed the symphony to cancel the performances because of concerns 
over artistic integrity stemming from threatened distruptions by 
people opposed to redgrave for her support of the palestine 
liberation organization 
the arguments were heard by a full fivemember panel of the 1st 
us circuit court of appeals which must decide whether to order a 
lower court judge to consider awarding redgrave additional damages 
for civil rights violations 
the justices gave no indication of when they would rule 
redgrave did not attend the hearing 
a threemember appeals panel in october ruled the symphony 
violated redgraves rights in canceling the 1982 performances the 
court then granted the symphonys motion asking for full court 
review of the 21 decision 
the symphony had hired redgrave to narrate six performances of 
stravinskys oedipus rex at boston tanglewood in western 
massachusetts and new yorks carnegie hall 
but it canceled the concerts after receiving letters and phone 
calls indicating there would be picketing and other protests 
because of redgraves support of the plo trial testimony also 
indicated symphony officials were warned that allowing redgrave to 
perform might cause it to lose some of its financial support from 
the jewish community 
in november 1984 a federal jury ruled the symphony had breached 
its contract with redgrave and awarded her the 27500 she was to 
have received for the performances plus 100000 in compensatory 
damages for work redgrave said she lost because of the action 
us district judge robert keeton threw out the 100000 award 
in february 1985 and ruled the symphony had not violated her civil 
rights the appeals court last october restored 12000 of that 
award the amount redgrave would have been paid for a broadway 
role she lost during the suit against the symphony 
at wednesdays hearing attorney daniel j kornstein said the 
symphony violated redgraves first amendment right of free speech 
in canceling a nonpolitical performance because of her political 
views 
its the public in deciding whether or not to purchase 
tickets which will determine the artistic intregrity in deciding 
whether to come or not kornstein argued 
but symphony attorney robert e sullivan argued that the 
protests would have prevented the symphony from presenting 
oedipus rex in the format it desired and that it has a first 
amendment right to decide what shows it will present 
this decision is at the core of what the first amendment is 
all about said sullivan who referred to language in 
massachusetts law that makes artistic integrity a valid defense in 
canceling a performance 
