<TEXT>
boeing co must justify to a jury its 
requirement that test and training pilots stop flying at age 60 and 
cant rely on a similar limit for commercial pilots a federal 
appeals court ruled wednesday 
the 9th us circuit court of appeals reinstated an age 
discrimination suit by the us equal employment opportunity 
commission against the seattlebased aircraft company 
according to the court boeing has 41 pilots who train other 
pilots and 24 who make test flights the company set its age60 
limit in 1980 forcing some pilots into layoffs or early 
retirement the eeoc said 
us district judge barbara rothstein dismissed the eeoc suit 
citing the federal aviation administrations longstanding rule 
requiring pilots of large commercial passenger planes to stop 
flying at 60 she said the faa rule was based on safety concerns 
that applied equally to boeing 
the appeals court said a jury must decide on the eeocs claim 
that it would be practical to examine pilots over 60 for 
disabilities rather than automatically disqualifying them under 
federal law the court said boeing must prove that individual 
testing is impractical 
the faa rule applies only to certain commercial pilots and the 
agency has expressly refused to apply the rule to other types of 
piliots said chief judge james browning in the 30 decision 
it may be that the age60 rule reflects an faa decision to 
resolve any doubts about the necessity for an age qualification in 
favor of the substantial number of passengers carried by the 
airlines covered by the rule browning said he said a court 
cannot assume that the same considerations would make an age60 
limit a business necessity for boeing 
browning who is 69 and recently announced his intention to step 
down as chief judge but remain an active member of the court said 
judge rothstein did not consider eeoc evidence of new scientific 
testing methods accurately predicting individual loss of function 
he said rothstein also disregarded evidence that boeing employed 
pilots over 60 without incident before 1980 that the navy had 
rescinded its age60 limit for pilots and that boeing and airlines 
have used elaborate testing procedures to allow pilots to resume 
flying after being grounded for alcoholism or heart disease 
there was also evidence that some of the work done by boeing 
pilots such as flight training was less stressful and dangerous 
than the jobs of commercial pilots browning said 
