a leading soviet expert on afghanistan said 
wednesday that the prokremlin regime in kabul may survive the 
withdrawal of the red army but that the lives of its leaders are 
in the hands of the almighty 
in a remarkably pessimistic public assessment for a soviet yuri 
gankovsky said the kabul regime controls about 30 percent of 
afghanistan including most administrative centers that tribal 
leaders control about 30 percent and that the islamic guerrillas 
known as mujahedeen control just over 30 percent 
the complicated balance of power hampers predictions of what 
will happen when and if the red army pulls out said gankovsky 
although some guerrillas have close ties with the fundamentalist 
moslem government in iran gankovsky said my impression is that 
an islamic republic in afghanistan is impossible because tribal 
leaders are so strong 
many us analysts believe that the prokremlin government will 
collapse immediately after a soviet pullout and that regime 
officials who do not leave will be targets of revenge from the 
families of the estimated 1 million afghans who were killed or the 
5 million afghans driven into exile during the war 
individual acts of revenge may take place gankovsky said 
but i hope that a blood bath will not take place 
it is impossible to predict the future of najib the leader 
of the kabul regime he said but we have the impression that the 
regime of the peoples democratic party may survive najib also 
known as najibullah uses a single name 
as for for the fate of najib and other leaders gankovsky said 
their life is in the hands of the almighty 
gankovsky in a lecture at the johns hopkins school of advanced 
international studies declined to speculate how many members of 
the current government might flee 
but he said that some middlesized leaders in kabul want to 
emigrate to the soviet union and other countries that is their 
private business 
gankovsky who retired last fall as head of the middle and near 
east section of the oriental institutes section of the soviet 
academy of sciences said he was unable to comment directly on 
stalled un negotiations designed to end the war 
the soviets say that us covert aid to the guerrillas should 
end within 60 days after an agreement is signed but pakistan 
representing the interests of the united states and the guerrillas 
insists that kremlin aid to kabul stop at the same time 
