asian city of tashkent on wednesday to meet with najib for talks 
thought to center on plans for a withdrawal of soviet troops even 
if the un talks collapse 
under the soviet system experts such as gankovsky not only 
write scholarly works but are asked to prepare classified reports 
for the key decisionmaking body on foreign relations the 
international department of the central committee secretariat 
gankovsky declined to say what advice he has the kremlin about 
afghanistan explaining that a lecture is not a confessional 
he denied that the soviet union plans to annex any part of 
afghanistan 
and he avoided direct comment on speculation that soviet 
withdrawal from afghanistan signalled an end to the socalled 
brezhnev doctrine invoked in the past to justify military 
intervention to prop up communist regimes in such nations such as 
hungary and czechoslovakia 
instead gankovsky clamed that afghanistan never had a communist 
government 
although najib and his colleagues represent a leftist faction 
within the ruling peoples democratic party of afghanistan said 
gankovsky there are not any communists among them 
the biggest part of them are afghan nationalists they are not 
communists they are not socialists he said drawing a fine line 
which was challenged vocally by some afghan emigres in the audience 
the chances that a prokremlin regime would prevail in 
afghanistan are bolstered by the high rate of party membership 75 
percent among military and police officials and by the large 
number of afghans 400000 employed by the state he said 
