<TEXT>
destruction of us mediumrange missiles 
under the new ussoviet nuclear arms reduction treaty will save 
the pentagon about 17 billion through the fall of 1995 the 
general accounting office reported wednesday 
the savings will come because the pentagon will no longer need 
to maintain its pershing and groundlaunched cruise missile force 
in western europe the gao said money will also be saved on 
associated costs for military personnel procurement and 
construction of housing for military family members it said 
army officials told us that some of the equipment procured 
under the pershing ii program would not be subject to treaty 
limitation and would therefore be available for use in other army 
units the ga0 said 
it said this includes radios trucks generators tool kits and 
other support equipment whose total value is unclear 
the air force it said has identified more than 550 million in 
equipment that will be reused and about 50 million in funding that 
will be recovered because of project cancellations 
for example the gao quoted air force officials as saying that 
76 launch control centers valued at about 6 million each for a 
total 456 million will be reused 
and it said about 114 million worth of missile components 
produced under existing air force contracts will be made available 
to the navy for its sealaunched cruise missile program 
the air force also expects to recover about 40 million to 58 
million in previously approved military construction funds 
according to the gao 
the treaty would require the united states to destroy a total of 
867 mediumrange missiles while the soviet union would be required 
to eliminate some 1800 weapons 
the us missiles to be destroyed over a 36month period 
beginning after the pact is ratified by the senate include 178 
pershing ias 247 pershing iis and 442 groundlaunched cruise 
missiles together with their launchers and certain support and 
training equipment 
the costs of actually destroying the weapons are classified and 
will be provided separately to members of congress the agency said 
the pentagon spent a total 65 billion for the pershing ii and 
groundlaunched cruise missile systems the gao said including 
26 billion for the pershings and 345 billion for the cruise 
missiles 
those totals include the costs of research and development 
procurement military construction and missile modifications 
the senate foreign relations committee voted 172 last month to 
recommend the full senate approve the treaty 
barring unexpected developments senate debate on the treaty is 
expected to begin late this month or in early may 
the gao report was requested by sen jesse helms rnc an 
opponent of the treaty 
