<TEXT>
the black codiscoverer of the north pole 
received what one supporter called long overdue recognition as 
his remains were reinterred with full military honors wednesday at 
arlington national cemetery 
matthew alexander henson was the first to reach the north pole 
and planted the american flag there exactly 79 years earlier during 
a trek with adm robert e peary and four eskimos 
peary was buried at arlington in 1920 and a huge monument to him 
was erected by his grave henson however ended up at his death in 
1955 in a shared grave at woodlawn cemetery in new york because his 
wife could not afford a separate gravesite 
he was denied proper recognition because of the racial 
attitudes of his time said dr s allen counter a harvard 
professor who successfully petitioned president reagan to allow 
hensons reinterment at arlington 
counter who previously had brought together hensons and 
pearys parteskimo offspring told about 100 relatives and 
admirers at the windswept hilltop burial site that the reinterment 
of henson and his wife lucy ross henson was long overdue 
recognition for our hero that would right a tragic wrong 
welcome home matthew henson he said welcome home to a 
new day in america may your presence here inspire generations 
of explorers 
hensons remains now rest alongside pearys with the remains of 
their wives on either side 
descendants of matthew and lucy henson were joined at the 
ceremony by hensons parteskimo descendants fathered when he was 
in the arctic 
now finally matthew henson and robert peary can talk about 
old days out there a grandson qitdlaq henson of qaanaaq 
greenland said through a translator at a news conference following 
the ceremony 
a monument installed next to the gravesite includes a quote from 
henson who was 88 when he died the lure of the arctic is 
tugging at my heart to me the trail is calling the old trail 
the trail that is always new 
although repeated references were made to pearys concern that 
hensons achievements be recognized none of pearys relatives 
attended the ceremony counter said 
im sorry theyre not here counter said at the news 
conference adding that he had invited both pearys son and 
grandson and had offered to help with travel arrangements he said 
that if he had known none of pearys american descendants were 
going to attend he would have invited his parteskimo offspring 
counter said the costs of the reinterments including exhuming 
the hensons from the new york cemetery the two bronze caskets the 
monument bringing hensons offspring from greenland and the rest 
of the arrangements ran into the thousands but he would not be 
more specific or say exactly who paid for what an aide ted doyle 
said counter took care of most of the bills 
gen julius beckton of the white house military office conveyed 
greetings from reagan who approved the reinterment last october 
all americans join us today in saluting matthew alexander 
henson as he receives the recognition he so long deserved 
beckton said 
among those speaking at the ceremony were john h johnson the 
chairman and chief executive officer of johnson publishing co 
which publishes ebony and jet magazines and col guion s bluford 
the first black astronaut 
matthew henson taught us all a great deal johnson said 
he taught us to be independent he taught us to achieve he 
never got the recognition he deserved but he never complained 
bluford described the ceremony as a proud and historic moment 
in americas history we not only pay homage to him but we 
remind future generations of his accomplishment and 
achievements he was the point man in one of mans greatest 
achievements 
