<TEXT>
the judge in the irancontra case signaled 
wednesday he was ready to discuss a realistic trial date to 
achieve an expeditious disposition of the criminal charges 
against the four defendants 
us district judge gerhard a gesell rejected as too cumbersome 
a proposal by independent counsel lawrence e walsh for elaborate 
procedures to prevent the unauthorized disclosure of 150000 pages 
of classified documents that may become evidence in the case 
walshs proposal appears to be far too complex lacks definite 
time restrictions and creates undue obstacles to the fair and 
expeditous disposition of this case gesell said in a brief 
opinion 
under the prosecution plan defense lawyers for former national 
security adviser john m poindexter lt col oliver north and arms 
dealers richard v secord and albert hakim would be required to 
obtain security clearances before they could examine the documents 
at a special compartmented information facility 
the four defendants are accused of conspiring to defraud the 
government by diverting some of the profits from the usiran arms 
sales to the nicaraguan rebels 
walshs propposal laid out intricate steps under the classified 
information procedures act for court review of sensitive documents 
that might be introduced by either side as evidence when the case 
goes to trial 
walsh said defense lawyers cannot begin examining the documents 
until adequate procedures are imposed by the court he said 
pretrial discovery could take three months 
but gesell said it will be necessary to frame a more limited 
protective order fashioned to the nature of this case which in 
essence alleges a course of conduct carried out using classified 
materials in classified channels from a highly classified site 
the judge said he wants to determine to what extent the 
documents will be made available available immediately for 
inspection by the defense 
at a hearing scheduled for next tuesday the court intends to 
determine the timing of discovery disclosures in relation to a 
realistic trial date gesell said 
gesell said he wants to set an april deadline for interagency 
review of the classified materials that have been collected during 
walshs 15month investigation and set a time for the defense to 
notify the court if it intends to use any secret documents as 
evidence 
under the classified information procedures act the defense is 
required to tell the court which material it will use the statute 
contains procedures for the court to review the documents to 
determine which if any are relevant to the proceedings 
the judge has the power to delete certain secret material and 
substitute statements of facts a particular document would prove 
the socalled graymail statute was enacted by congress in 
1980 to facilitate prosecution of espionage cases and to control 
the disclosure of classified information at trial 
the procedures were envisioned to balance secrecy with the 
governments need to use classified documents as evidence 
representatives of the defense department the cia the national 
security council the fbi and the justice department are reviewing 
the documents assembled by walsh to determine if any can be 
declassified 
in his pleadings walsh said the documents describe in detail 
some of the nations most carefully held secrets about its foreign 
policy its intelligence activities and its covert activities 
the defendants filed a joint opposition to walshs motion for 
expedited consideration of the proposed protective order noting 
that north and poindexter had access to many of the documents when 
they were at the national security council 
the defense motion said walshs proposal raised a number of 
issues about the constitutionality of the classified information 
law as well as the independent counsels power to represent the 
governments national security interests 
</TEXT>
