president daniel ortega warned the 
contra rebels wednesday that if ceasefire talks break down the 
government will begin a major military offensive 
if the contras dont accept the agreements the people must be 
ready for combat and launch an offensive with all available 
force to be rid of the contras once and for all and not prolong 
the war he said in remarks carried on the state radio voice of 
nicaragua 
earlier in the day the radio reported that contra and 
sandinista military representatives agreed on seven zones where 
rebels will gather during their 60day ceasefire 
the two sides remained far apart however on key issues to 
bring about a permanent peace 
the sandinistas launched an offensive against the contras in 
northern nicaragua last month on president reagans orders 3200 
us troops flew to honduras on march 1718 after honduran 
president jose azcona hoyo said 2000 nicaraguan soldiers had 
invaded his country in pursuit of contras 
the us troops never saw action and returned home at the end of 
march 
wednesdays meeting in the southern border town of sapoa the 
fourth set of talks in less than a month dealt with the mechanics 
of pursuing the truce which went into effect friday 
the voice of nicaragua broadcasting from sapoa said boundaries 
were set for two zones in the north two in central nicaragua two 
on the remote caribbean coast and one in the south 
just about all the details were defined about the location and 
dimension of the zones but tomorrow the method of operation will 
be discussed maj gen joaquin cuadra lacayo chief of the 
sandinista delegation said in a broadcast interview after 
discussions recessed for the day 
cuadra is chief of staff of the sandinista army 
the contras are to gather in the zones during the first 15 days 
of april it still must be decided how to provide security 
assurances for the rebels and how humanitarian assistance can be 
delivered to them 
on march 23 the two sides formally agreed to the truce as part 
of a plan to end a war that killed or wounded an estimated 50000 
people over nearly seven years 
neither the leftist sandinista government nor the nicaraguan 
resistance the ussupported contra rebel organization says it 
is satisfied with the other sides compliance with the accord 
contra leaders accused the sandinistas of violating a section of 
the pact that calls for unrestricted freedom of expression by 
failing to supply newsprint to nicaraguas only opposition 
newspaper la prensa 
at a news conference wednesday la prensa publisher violeta 
barrios de chamorro called the newsprint restriction a deliberate 
blow to freedom of expression in nicaragua 
the accord also called for the release of 100 political 
prisoners on march 27 the contras complain the sandinistas freed 
only 10 of the prisoners the rebels had on their list although the 
pact does not specify the rebels have a say in who goes free 
issues still pending include how and when the contras will lay 
down their weapons this is not spelled out in the plan nor does 
the plan say what will happen to the contras after they gather in 
the zones 
under the plan the government pledges that the individuals 
who have been reintegrated into normal civilian life will be able 
to take part in future elections 
but normal civilian life is open to interpretation in 
nicaragua where the government claims to have 300000 people under 
arms 
the contras backed out of a highlevel meeting to continue 
definitive ceasefire negotiations originally set for wednesday 
in managua the capital they said the meeting must wait until 
security issues for the rebels were resolved 
the two sides are arguing about an agenda for the next meeting 
as well as a date 
in addition the contras insist that their 55member delegation 
stay at managuas downtown intercontinental hotel and be free to 
meet with political opposition leaders 
maria teresa zambrana head of reservations at the hotel said 
wednesday the contras have reserved 50 rooms for april 1215 
the sandinistas have said that for security reasons the contra 
delegation would be housed at a hotel near the airport 
