<TEXT>
the state department hired at least one 
company linked to earlier drug smuggling to transport aid to the 
usbacked contra rebels in nicaragua and was put in touch with 
the company by the cia according to congressional testimony and 
sources 
the departments nicaraguan humanitarian assistance office in 
early 1986 signed a series of contracts totaling more than 300000 
with vortex a small miami air transport and service company to 
airlift humanitarian aid to the rebels michael b palmer an 
admitted former drug pilot who then worked for vortex said 
wednesday 
the company was unprepared to handle the volume of supplies the 
state department wanted transported and had to rent a larger 
warehouse to accommodate the job palmer told the senate foreign 
relations narcotics subcommittee 
vortex also did airplane maintenance work for cia proprietary 
companies resupplying the contras in 1987 and in late 1986 sold 
the cia supply operation a dc6 that formerly had been used to haul 
drugs according to his testimony and committee staff members 
investigators for the congressional irancontra committees have 
told the narcotics panel that the state department selected vortex 
from a list of transport companies provided by the cia according 
to a senate committee source speaking on condition of anonymity 
if the contra delivery system is using known narcotics dealers 
for airlifts its no wonder you have confusion surrounding the 
policy said subcommittee chairman sen john kerry dmass 
it was unclear whether the department knew that it was hiring a 
company with drug links to undertake part of the resupply 
operation robert duemling who ran the nhao was expected to 
testify before the panel on thursday 
kerry said the arrangement illustrated the absurdity not to 
mention the impropriety of a government contract going to someone 
with drug involvement handing out us taxpayer dollars to 
support their business 
somethings wrong here kerry said a contractor to nhao 
flying in an exdrug plane working simultaneously in narcotics 
undercover and supplying goods to the contras 
but palmer said that was part of the reality of drug enforcement 
efforts he said agencies dont have the money to own their own 
aircraft for undercover operations or the desire to undertake such 
risky ventures themselves 
enter sf a 27 million state department 
effort to deliver nonlethal supplies to the contras authorized by 
congress in 1985 the general accounting office later sharply 
criticized the operation saying large amounts of the aid could not 
be accounted for 
wednesdays hearing was part of a continuing series of sessions 
kerry said are intended to alert the public and policymakers to the 
pervasiveness of drug trading throughout latin america later 
witnesses kerry said will establish even stronger links between 
drug trafficking and resupply efforts for the contras 
palmer was arrested on marijuana smuggling charges in michigan 
in 1986 along with others while working for the state department 
and acting at the same time as an informant for the drug 
enforcement administration and the customs service others charged 
at that time were convicted but palmers indictment was dropped 
because of his role in helping the government he testified 
palmer said the decision to drop charges against him was made 
locally in detroit and was due to circumstances surrounding an 
undercover operation and did not involve washington higherups or 
the contra connection 
but kerry said there had been a washington meeting about 
disposition of palmers case and that the question of who prompted 
his release remained open 
