<TEXT>
a mainline american denomination the american 
baptist churches is backing away from its support of abortion 
rights officials indicated this week 
it was the first such definitive shift projected among the 
larger socially activist protestant bodies 
similar reassessments have come in some other major 
denominations either stiffening opposition to abortion or 
qualifying acceptance of it but some still take an essentially 
prochoice position 
the turn away from it planned by american baptists stemmed both 
from simmering discontent with the past stance and the swelling 
tide of abortions in the country 
the great proliferation of abortion has made us stop and look 
at whats happening here says gloria marshall of alto loma 
calif head of a task force which has been reexamining the issue 
for more than two years 
its a process of reevaluation and reassessment she said in 
a telephone interview this is a continuing necessity if the 
church is to carry out its prophetic role on such a key social 
issue 
she said positions cant be fixed in concrete but are 
pulled along by social changes on the issue and as we understand 
more about it she termed the projected new stand 
responsibility to choose life 
it attempts a pathbreaking middle ground 
it is a prolife stance in affirming the sacredness of life as 
a gift of god she said but it avoids both the prolife and 
prochoice terms commonly used in the polarized conflict over 
abortion 
mrs marshall a former missionary in zaire and wife of a 
minister said weve sought a different vocabulary for dealing 
with a very complex subject weve tried to find a common ground 
for ministering to people about it 
the newly prepared statement expected to be approved in a final 
presentation to a policymaking general board in june acknowledges 
keen diversity among the denominations 16 million members on the 
issue 
howevever the statement breaks with the previous 1981 stand 
which saw abortion in terms of religious liberty as a matter of 
responsible personal choice 
the new document recognizing life as a sacred and gracious 
gift of god says 
as american baptists we oppose abortion as a means of 
avoiding responsibility for conception as a primary means of birth 
control without regard for the farreaching consequences of the 
act 
we denounce irresponsible sexual behavior and acts of sexual 
violence that contribute to the large number of abortions each year 
we grieve with all who struggle with the difficult 
circumstances that lead them to consider abortion recognizing that 
each person is ultimately responsible to god we encourage women 
and men in these circumstances to seek spiritual counsel as they 
prayerfully and conscientiously consider their decision 
a sister church the larger 146million southern baptist 
convention takes a firmly antiabortion position toughening that 
stand in 1984 to ask for laws prohibiting all abortion except to 
save the physical life of the mother 
changes also have come among more liberal mainline bodies 
including 
the presbyterian church usa in 1985 qualified its acceptance 
of choice in the matter opposing abortion as a method of birth 
control or for convenience or to ease embarrassment 
the church of the brethren in 1984 explicitly condemned 
abortion after previously taking a more pastoral view of it 
the former lutheran church in america now merged into the 
evangelical lutheran church in america in 1980 sharpened its 
rejection of abortion saying it destroys life and urged laws 
protecting it from conception to birth 
numerous denominations have steadily rejected abortion 
including eastern orthodox churches roman catholicism the 
lutheran churchmissouri synod mormons and conservative 
evangelical denominations 
however several mainline bodies such as the united methodist 
church episcopal church united church of christ and christian 
church disciples of christ uphold choice about abortion and the 
legalizing of it 
the sevenmember american baptist task force including three 
supporters of legalized abortion three opponents and one 
undetermined about it has held hearings across the country 
gathered questionaires and a flood of letters 
mary mild staff assistant on the project at the denominations 
headquarters in valley forge pa said there has been some 
discontent with the previous stance of 1981 enough people were 
not happy with it as reflecting where we really are she said 
the revision expresses no opinion of the 1973 supreme court 
decision legalizing abortion neither for nor against but condemns 
harassing either abortion clinics or doctors refusing to do 
abortions 
the sevenpage statement stresses education and ministry to 
reinforce responsible sexuality to help those facing problem 
pregnancies and to provide needed financial aid to women carrying 
such pregnancies to birth 
while not citing any circumstances that justify abortion as was 
done previously the new statement urges a ministry of love and 
spiritual counsel to those who choose to terminate their 
pregnancies 
</TEXT>
