<TEXT>
interest rates have edged higher in recent 
weeks but most economists see no cause for alarm because there is 
little evidence that the driving force of the rise is higher 
inflation 
inflation remains under control in spite of surprisingly strong 
economic growth economists say 
there is a lot of skepticism about inflation i think its 
healthy but probably unwarranted thomas f carpenter vice 
president and economics director for asb capital management a 
washingtonbased pension fund manager said tuesday 
consumer prices are rising at an annual rate of about 4 percent 
to 45 percent roughly the same as in the past three years 
the concern about inflation is a sharp contrast to opinions that 
prevailed after the oct 19 stock market crash then interest 
rates fell because investors felt the crash might trigger a 
recession and curb inflation 
rates for 30year fixedrate mortgages fell from about 116 
percent just before the stock market crash last october to a little 
over 98 percent by february according to the federal home loan 
mortgage corp known as freddie mac 
instead of crashing though the economy has created more than 1 
million jobs since october the jobless rate fell to 56 percent in 
march the lowest in nine years 
some investors changed their minds and decided the economy was 
in danger of overheating and high inflation mortgage rates 
consequently have crept back to just over 10 percent nationwide as 
of april 1 freddie mac says 
inflation fears drive up interest rates because investors demand 
higher yields to make up for the erosion of the value of 
fixedincome investments that inflation causes 
americans are paying unusually high interest rates now because 
creditmarket investors were burned by doubledigit inflation in 
the 1970s and early 1980s and keep thinking those days might come 
again 
despite the fears of last october many economists now have 
concluded the stock market crash was good for the economy because 
it cooled off an economy that was overheating 
steep recessions generally are preceded by inflationary 
overheating which leads to high interest rates that in turn choke 
off economic growth 
in the current economy inflation hasnt had a chance to 
accelerate because the credit markets have reacted so quickly to 
it driving up interest rates and cooling the economy before it 
overheats said alan lerner a managing director and financial 
economist for bankers trust co 
in a sense lerner said the economy has become selfcorrecting 
through the bond markets sensitivity to inflation that may 
explain why the economy remains in the longest peacetime expansion 
of the 20th century 
the bond market is running the economic show both globally and 
domestically carpenter said bond managers in effect are in 
the drivers seat 
some economists believe the federal reserve the nations 
central bank has engineered the recent uptick in interest rates 
according to that theory the fed is trying to prove its 
inflationfighting credentials to the bond market it is heading 
off a steep rise in interest rates over the long term by pushing 
them up slightly in the short term 
the federal reserve reaction is appropriate said george 
gols an analyst for arthur d little inc in boston to prepare 
for inflationary surges is much better than to do it afterward 
but other economists say fed action if any has been modest 
one reason might be that any attempt by the fed to cool off the 
economy with higher interest rates would punish the housing market 
which is relatively weak 
if the fed is doing anything theyre just raising the flag 
and saying hey were here were not oblivious to whats going 
on in the world said robert chandross chief economist in the 
north american head office of lloyds bank of london 
the yield of the widely watched 30year treasury bond has ticked 
up to about 89 percent this week from a recent low of less than 
83 percent in early february 
carpenter said the bond probably would go no higher than 93 
percent and no lower than 83 percent in the rest of 1988 lerner 
said it might edge up to 95 or even 97 percent by the end of the 
year gols who is in a small minority of economists predicting a 
recession by the end of 1988 predicted the long bonds yield would 
rise slightly and then trend steadily downward 
</TEXT>
