<TEXT>
gd searle amp co is broadening its program to 
give free drugs to the the poor to include all of its medication 
for heart disease 
last year searle began providing its high blood pressure 
medicine to people who could not afford to buy it and had no 
insurance now all seven of its drugs that treat cardiovascular 
problems will be available to poor people without charge said dr 
sheldon g gilgore chairman and chief executive officer 
i personally believe that all drugs that treat 
lifethreatening diseases should be involved gilgore said in a 
telephone interview tuesday but cardiovascular drugs are about 
all we make 
no one who suffers from cardiovascular disease should be denied 
medication because they cant afford it he said 
searle which is based in skokie ill is inviting all 
physicians in the nation to participate in the program which cost 
the company 9 million last year 
bill greener a senior vice president said searle does not know 
how much the expanded program will cost but he said the company 
expects it will double the existing program 
theres no money limit on it he said 
gilgore said the company will deliver 1 million worth of 
certificates to clinics and hospitals in 10 major cities today to 
dramatize the expansion of its patient in need program 
any physician clinic or hospital in the nation may request 
searle certificates for needy patients 
the company sets broad guidelines for patients to qualify but 
leaves it up to the individual physician to make the decision 
the company is mailing instructions to doctors that classify 
poor people as those with annual household incomes of 8000 for 
one or two people or 11000 for three or more family members to 
qualify patients must not have insurance or other assistance that 
would pay for the drug 
its up to the doctor to determine but the patient doesnt 
have to bring in tax returns or anything like that said gilgore 
we believe the doctor knows who his poor patients are 
searle launched the pilot program with two drugs that treat high 
blood pressure in february 1987 twentythousand patients have 
received free medication 
the new expanded program includes five additional products used 
to treat high blood pressure angina arrhythmias and congestive 
heart failure 
the american pharmaceutical industry can satisfy the unmet 
prescription needs of the medically indigent patient population in 
this country gilgore said 
judee shuler of the pharmaceutical manufacturers association in 
washington dc said tuesday that all pharmaceutical companies do 
something but searle is more extensive at working with the 
healthcare delivery system 
she said the other companies will help out in individual need 
cases or in thirdworld countries but she said she knows of no 
other pharmaceutical company doing the same kind of work as searle 
searle is a researchbased company which develops manufactures 
and markets prescription pharmaceuticals worldwide it is a wholly 
owned subsidiary of monsanto co 
twothirds of searles sales are in cardiovascular drugs 
greener said the other third is primarily oral contraceptives he 
said 
