the chicago board of trade while other commodities were mixed in a 
narrow range 
follow through buying from tuesdays strong runup kept the wheat 
pit busy said victor lespinasse a trader with dean witter 
reynolds inc 
after the close of trading on tuesday the agriculture 
department announced that it is offering china 2 million tons of 
subsidized wheat 
this and an expected soviet bid thursday on a half million tons 
of wheat put traders into a buying mood said lespinasse 
soybean futures opened a little easier following weaker european 
markets but firmed up a little in early dealings in chicago 
on the opening wheat was 2 cents to 3 cents higher with the 
contract for delivery in may at 309 a bushel corn was unchanged 
to cent lower with may at 208 a bushel oats were 1 cent to 1 
cents higher with may at 167 a bushel and soybeans were 3 cents 
