<TEXT>
us trade representative clayton yeutter told 
the governments of britain france west germany and spain on 
wednesday they are risking a trade war by their enormous 
subsidies to airbus passenger planes 
the major trade bill now before congress would permit the 
charging of extra countervailing duties on imports of the 
airbus they would be designed to compensate for the subsidies 
raising the price of the foreign planes and thus improving the 
chances of us aircraft manufacturers making sales to airlines 
here 
the longer these governments delay in coming to grips with 
their own subsidies for airbus the more they heighten the risk of 
a major trade conflict yeutter said in a statement 
with the statement yeutters office distributed a detailed 
refutation of a report on march 18 by airbus industrie the 
consortium that makes the planes on us subsidies to aircraft 
manufacturers he criticized the report as containing poor 
scholarship and false conclusions 
it said the us government had provided about 23 billion in 
direct and indirect subsidies over the past decade to boeing co 
and mcdonnell douglas corp 
us trade officials have long complained that the european 
subsidies give european aircraft builders an unfair advantage over 
us companies 
the us does not directly support civil aircraft programs 
yeutter said it is the four european governments that have 
lavished gigantic sums on airbus for nearly two decades despite the 
programs inability to show any profit 
he said he expects to see members of the european governments in 
paris in midmay and would like to discuss indirect subsidies 
before then 
we will not hold such discussions on the basis of a study 
that has no credibility he said 
after the last negotiations at constance west germany on march 
18 yeutter said a first step had been taken in a prospective 
agreement on production subsidies but that there was still a long 
way to go on subsidies for research and development 
the statement issued by yeutters office said the us 
government buys goods for its own needs and not to benefit any 
manufacturer when major contractors make profits they can spend 
them as they will it added 
by contrast the airbus partners must spend the money supplied 
to them by their governments on commercial airplane development and 
nothing else the statement said 
</TEXT>
