<TEXT>
japanese investors bought 1277 billion 
worth of us real estate in 1987 a 70 percent increase over the 
previous year according to a new report 
the purchases were concentrated in markets traditionally favored 
by the japanese hawaii california and new york but investors 
are broadening their sights to include other areas as well 
according to a study released wednesday 
the study conducted for the last three years by kenneth 
laventhal amp co a nationwide accounting firm is based on 
information from clients public records and other sources and is 
described by the company as a slight underestimation 
the buying binge is spurred by the rising value of the yen in 
relation to the dollar the tight real estate market in japan and 
attractive rates of return on us commercial real estate ranging 
from 6 percent to 9 percent a year said jack rodman managing 
partner of the companys los angeles office 
japanese real estate purchases mushroomed in the three years of 
the study 186 billion in 1985 753 billion in 1986 and 1277 
billion in 1987 
in 1987 hawaii was the favorite shopping spot attracting 33 
billion from japan the study found california was second with 
298 billion and new york was third with 234 billion 
far behind in order were arizona illinois texas washington 
state florida washington dc and massachusetts 
office buildings commanded the most dollars from japan 519 
billion in 1987 investment in hotel and resort properties soared 
160 percent in 1987 to 457 billion partly because of several 
big purchases in hawaii investment in residential property was 
13 billion 
