<TEXT>
representatives of chrysler corp 
workers voted wednesday to seek the job protections and economic 
benefits won by the united auto workers union in contracts signed 
last fall with general motors corp and ford motor co 
weve had a pattern settlement before us now for almost a 
year it should not take a long time for us to put this 
together uaw president owen bieber told reporters after 
addressing the 140member uaw national chrysler council 
chrysler and the uaw agreed to open talks early april 18 
instead of midjuly after chryslers attempt to sell its 
28000worker acustar inc subsidiary sparked bitter worker 
opposition 
chrysler backed down from the sale in early march shortly after 
the issue erupted but decided the damage left in its wake would 
intensify if the two sides waited until july to meet at the 
bargaining table 
bieber said he didnt believe the rift would hurt the chance of 
an early settlement mirroring the industrypattern gm and ford 
contracts 
i dont plan on sitting in early negotiations with chrysler 
from the time we open here in april until sept 14 when 
chryslers contract expires bieber said adding that bargainers 
will set a target settlement deadline after talks begin 
bieber also said negotiators would try to save four acustar 
plants that chrysler said it will close or sell 
the chrysler contract covers 59000 active and 8000 laidoff 
workers at 49 local unions the uaw wants a twoyear contract with 
chrysler instead of the usual threeyear pact so that its contracts 
with all big three automakers will expire together in 1990 
uaw vice president marc stepp said the council will vote 
thursday on other demands and on a potentially divisive issue 
whether nearly 1000 former american motors corp workers at an 
engine and stamping plant in kenosha wis should be included 
under the chrysler contract 
some local union leaders said they oppose the idea because if 
the kenosha engine plant closes those workers would have the right 
to take jobs that otherwise could go to laidoff chrysler workers 
chrysler already has said it will close a 5500worker assembly 
plant in kenosha by years end and those workers will be covered 
under a separate closing agreement all the kenosha workers belong 
to the uaw but currently work under contracts negotiated with amc 
not chrysler 
stepp said the union traditionally has included operations 
purchased by an automaker under that companys national contract 
other union officials who asked not to be identified called 
the opposition selfish and argued that the kenosha workers already 
are part of chrysler which bought amc last year 
proposals approved wednesday would like the pattern gm and ford 
contracts forbid plant closings not announced before the start of 
negotiations the unions proposals for chrysler also would ban 
sale of plants or other operations according to the printed 
resolutions approved by the council 
the ford and gm agreements also forbid layoffs for any reason 
except slow sales of a product the exception seen as a loophole 
by many workers has allowed gm to indefinitely close plants that 
make products whose sales were lagging 
but bieber said any loophole would most likely be addressed in 
1990 talks rather than at the chrysler table this year 
under the pattern workers also will receive bonuses equal to 3 
percent of their 1988 and 1989 earnings and a share of 
salesgenerated profits if their companies earn above a set amount 
the uaw also wants to increase its representation on chryslers 
board of directors already unique in the auto industry from one 
seat to four the current seat belongs to the uaw president and 
bieber said it gives him an extra chance to try influencing some 
corporate decisions that affect his members 
with three other uaw members on the board bieber joked it 
wouldnt be a 191 vote anymore im convinced i could convince my 
uaw colleagues to vote with me 
