<TEXT>
millionaire industrialist victor posner said 
wednesday he does not want a judge to set aside his setence for tax 
evasion that grants five years probation on the condition he set 
up a 3 million program for the homeless 
posner responded to a motion filed monday by a federal 
prosecutor challenging the legality of that sentence us attorney 
leon kellner said the court could not force a defendant to make a 
contribution to a nonaggrieved person 
at a hearing wednesday us district judge eugene p spellman 
required the 69yearold posner to state under oath that he did not 
wish the sentence set aside and that he was going ahead with the 
plan freely and voluntarily 
spellman said posners chief attorney edward bennett williams 
must formally reply to kellners motion within 30 days 
meanwhile spellman heard posner and a 10member blueribbon 
committee discuss the programs first stage a study of 
homelessness in three southern florida counties 
since february i have been studying and learning about the 
problems of the homeless both nationally and in florida posner 
said in a brief statement part of his sentence has included work 
at camillus house a refuge for the homeless in miami where posner 
served food attended substance abuse meetings and gave out 
clothing 
posner said the study which is being administered by barry 
university will examine groups such as alcoholics the mentally 
ill and families with children and will review how government 
policies affect homelessness findings of the study are scheduled 
to be available by midmay 
but he stressed that the study is not the most important element 
of the program 
all the studies in the world will not help one homeless 
person posner added i will come to you with what will solve 
the problem 
spellman said he didnt plan to take an active role in the 
committees work but he suggested the initial study not use more 
than 250000 to 500000 of posners donation 
posner said he was ready to deposit the necessary money in any 
institution directed by the court 
the sentence also ordered posner to pay about 4 million in back 
taxes penalties interest and fines for pleading nocontest to 10 
counts of tax fraud for inflating the value of land donated to 
miami christian college 
spellman acknowledged when he imposed the sentence that its 
legality might be questioned 
if for some reason the sentence is ever challenged this 
court will in fact incarcerate victor posner he said in 
february posner could be sentenced to up to 40 years in prison for 
the offenses 
